6	//! Value mapping: MIR locals → alloca slots and associated helper ops.
7	//!
8	//! Every non-ZST MIR local is backed by a single `mir.alloca` emitted at the
9	//! top of the function's entry block. Defs lower to `mir.store` and uses to
10	//! `mir.load`. This module owns the per-local slot map and the emitters for
11	//! the three slot operations.
12	//!
13	//! The `mem2reg` pass in `pipeline.rs` promotes the scalar slots back into
14	//! SSA before LLVM lowering, so at steady state the only `mir.alloca`s that
15	//! survive are those whose addresses actually escape.
16	//!
17	//! # Slot address-space inference
18	//!
19	//! Rust's reference / raw-pointer types carry no address-space information
20	//! (`&mut f32`, `*const u32` all translate to a generic `MirPtrType`). On
21	//! GPU, however, intermediate locals frequently end up holding pointers in
22	//! a concrete address space — e.g. `let p = &mut TILE_A[i]` on a
23	//! `SharedArray` produces an `addrspace(3)` pointer, yet the Rust local is
24	//! typed `&mut f32` (generic).
25	//!
26	//! Picking the slot's addrspace from Rust's declared type alone causes every
27	//! store of such a concrete-addrspace pointer to go through a
28	//! `mir.cast <PtrToPtr>` → LLVM `addrspacecast` → PTX `cvta.shared.u64`,
29	//! and subsequent loads of that pointer to hit the generic (runtime-
30	//! dispatched) store path instead of native `st.shared.*`.
31	//!
32	//! [`SlotAddrSpaceMap`] is a pre-scan over the MIR body that, per local,
33	//! infers the pointee address space from the *writes* into that local. The
34	//! answer is used by `body::emit_entry_allocas` via
35	//! [`align_pointer_addr_space`] to pick an alloca pointee that matches what
36	//! actually gets stored.
